******
[1] Brazil
Date: Thu 5 Jun 2008
Source: UAI [in Portuguese, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.uai.com.br:80/UAI/html/sessao_2/2008/06/05/em_noticia_interna,id_sessao=2&id_noticia=65945/em_noticia_interna.shtml>


The cases of dengue reported in Minas Gerais in the 1st 5 months of this
year [2008] reached 42 500. Last year [2007], there were 44 000
notifications of people [with dengue] infected by [virus carried by] the
_Aedes aegypti_ mosquito. Some municipalities in the eastern region and the
Mata zone suffered epidemics, mainly in April [2008], when the records
reached levels above those expected. In 2008, 7 deaths from the disease
were confirmed in the state, with 3 from DHF [dengue hemorrhagic fever] and
4 from complications.

In Belo Horizonte, the [dengue] notifications are following an increasing
pattern. The number of people who contracted the disease in the 1st
semester was higher than last year [2007]. [The number this year] is 8384
[dengue] patients versus 5235 in [2007]. In 2006, there were 664 cases and
in 2005, only 68. The patients also have suffered more serious forms [of
dengue], with 3 deaths in [the state] capital, 16 cases with complications
and with DHF.

The 3rd death in Belo Horizonte, was confirmed this week, with the death on
Friday [30 May 2008] of a 39 year old teacher of the state [education] network.

According to the manager of surveillance in health and information of the
Municipal Secretariat of Health, Celeste Rodrigues Souza, at this time of
year, with the low temperatures and the period of increased drought, there
has been a reduction in cases of dengue. The registry already registered a
drop in [dengue case] notifications and also a reduction the number of
people seeking attention at the health centers, urgent care units, and
hospital beds. This is an opportune moment for preventive action. "We must
invest in actions to prevent and eliminate the foci of the mosquito before
the rainy season," warned Celeste Souza.

Some actions [that have been] implemented this year [2008] to halt the
spread of the explosion of [dengue] cases, mainly in the Northeast region,
which had 4473 infected people, should be continued throughout the year.
This work was done in partnership with the Superintendency of Urban
Sanitation, and more than 1.5 million tons of garbage and materials that
serve as water receptacles for _ Aedes aegypti_ were collected.

Another action that should be done during the year is [action against
mosquito] invasion of closed buildings. Up to the present, 49 houses were
hit with fines. "These actions are justified in times of greater
transmission [and of dengue] cases, but we are reaching the conclusion that
in terms real impact and to avoid the disease we must extend these measures
over the entire year, " said Celeste Souza.

[byline: Luciana Melo]

--
