[2] Peru
Date: Sat 24 May 2008
Source: Epidemiological Bulletin (Lima) 2008; 17(21), 2008 [in Spanish,
trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.oge.sld.pe/boletines/2008/21.pdf>


In epidemiological week (EW) 21 (18-24 May 2008), 98 cases of classical
dengue were reported to the Directorate General of Epidemiology (DGE); 90
per cent of the reported cases are from the regional health directorates
(DIRESA): Piura II (42 cases), Piura I (19 cases), Jaen (16 cases), and
Lambayeque (11 cases). The Loreto DIRESA has not provided reports this week.

The cumulative number of dengue cases reported to the DGE [for 2008] are
7391 through EW 21, of which 1566 cases were laboratory confirmed, 4256 are
probable [dengue cases], and 1569 were ruled out.

Concerning DHF, through EW 21 (2008) 21 cases were reported of which 12
were [laboratory] confirmed. No deaths have been reported to date.

In Lima, [in 2008] to the present week, 159 cases have been reported of
which 108 were discarded, 31 are under study (probable [dengue cases]) and
20 have been [laboratory] confirmed. All of the confirmed cases were
imported [from other parts of the country]. None of the confirmed cases
were contracted in Lima.

Concerning the dengue virus serotypes, all 4 virus types have been detected
in 2008, of which DEN 2 [virus] was circumscribed to Madre de Dios and DEN
3 [virus] occurred in Sullana, Loreto, Lambayeque, and Ucayali. Classical
dengue with hemorrhagic manifestations was attributed to the latter [virus].

